Now that we feel like we’ve got the right expressions  for transmission 
and reflection, we make a few observations about our results.  The 
first is that, even though the energy of the particle is above the 
barrier, there is still some probability that the particle will be 
reflected.  Note that this would not be true for a classical particle; in 
that case, there would be 100% probability of transmission if the 
energy was above the barrier and 0% chance of reflection.  The 
situation here is more reminiscent of classical waves, which typically 
split into two traveling waves whenever an obstacle is encountered.  
This “below barrier reflection” is another example of t he particle-wave 
duality in QM. 
 
