This is the source of the often-used blanket statement that  “the 
wavefunction always decays exponentially in the classically forbidden 
region. ”  This is not rigorously true, since the wavefu nction can often 
decay either faster or slower than an exponential in a classically 
forbidden region.  However, in general this idea is qualitatively 
correct. Note that, in the classically forbidden case there is no 
transmission. Because the wavefunction decays exponentially to the 
right of the barrier, the probability of finding the particle far to the right 
is vanishingly small.  However, there is a small amount of barrier 
penetration; it is possible to find the particle just inside the barrier, 
before the decaying component has fallen to zero.  This is called 
